        <h3>Rising unit costs</h3>
        <p>Chronic overtime, excess headcount, and misaligned labor supply are driving up the cost of every unit you produce.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>High turnover on off-shifts</h3>
        <p>You can't keep people on nights and weekends. Competitors with better schedules are poaching your trained workforce.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Expanding to 24/7</h3>
        <p>The leap from 5-day to continuous operations is the biggest workforce change most facilities face. Employees fear the unknown.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Coverage gaps and absenteeism</h3>
        <p>Unplanned absences, FMLA, and skill imbalances leave machines idle and supervisors scrambling every week.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Fatigue and safety concerns</h3>
        <p>Long shifts, early starts, and poor rotation patterns are degrading alertness and increasing incident risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>A past change went badly</h3>
        <p>You tried to change schedules before and it failed — or succeeded technically but destroyed trust. You need a different approach.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Too many schedules</h3>
        <p>Departments running different patterns create coordination problems, skill imbalances, and management headaches.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Seasonal or volatile demand</h3>
        <p>Fixed schedules can't flex with your workload. You need a system that absorbs variability without burning people out.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge-card">
        <h3>Greenfield or expansion</h3>
        <p>New facility, new line, or consolidation. You have one chance to set the schedule right from the start.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
